  "prompt": "How different is the Indian education system from the Finnish education system?",
  "response": "The Indian and Finnish education systems are quite different in several key aspects:\n\n1. Approach to Education\n- India: Highly competitive, exam-focused, rote learning\n- Finland: Holistic, student-centered, emphasizes learning over testing\n\n2. Curriculum\n- India: Rigid, standardized curriculum with heavy emphasis on academic subjects\n- Finland: Flexible curriculum, interdisciplinary learning, focus on creativity\n\n3. Examination\n- India: Frequent high-stakes exams, competitive entrance tests\n- Finland: Minimal standardized testing, continuous assessment\n\n4. Teaching Methods\n- India: Teacher-centered, lecture-based instruction\n- Finland: Interactive, collaborative learning, fewer teaching hours\n\n5. Teacher Training\n- India: Less rigorous teacher training programs\n- Finland: Highly selective, extensive teacher training (Master's degree required)\n\n6. Private vs. Public Education\n- India: Significant private school sector, varied quality\n- Finland: Predominantly public education, high-quality and uniform\n\n7. School Hours\n- India: Longer school days, more homework\n- Finland: Shorter school days, less homework, more play and leisure time\n\n8. Funding and Resources\n- India: Uneven resource distribution, significant urban-rural divide\n- Finland: Consistent, well-funded education system with equal resources\n\nThese differences reflect contrasting educational philosophies and socio-economic contexts.",
